<subSubSection pageId="361" pageNumber="362" type="reference_group">
<paragraph pageId="361" pageNumber="362">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Maddison" authorityYear="2008" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Bembidion" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="361" pageNumber="362" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rothfelsi">Bembidion rothfelsi</taxonomicName>
Maddison, 2008: 167. Type locality: &quot;Ottauquechee River, Bridgewater (250 m), Windsor Co[unty], Vermont&quot; (original citation). Holotype (♂) in USNM. Etymology. The specific name was proposed in honor of Klaus Rothfels [1919-1987], one of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Canada’s">Canada's</normalizedToken>
outstanding cytogeneticists. Working at the University of Toronto, Rothfels specialized on the evolutionary analysis of speciation in black flies.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="361" pageNumber="362" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="361" pageNumber="362">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="361" pageNumber="362">This species ranges from Cape Breton Island to east-central Missouri, south to southwestern Mississippi and southern North Carolina along the Appalachian Mountains [see Maddison 2008: Fig. 19].</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
